<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-09-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-09-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="398" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d398">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 123.G35/52.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé
                                    d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-09-06">
                                    <hi rend="italic">September 6, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I have just been informed by the Secretary of State that yesterday he
                            appealed to the newspapers of Habana to cease their campaign of abuse
                            and that they all promised to do so. He made it clear that there was no
                            foundation for the attacks on me and that the guilty papers will make a
                            full apology. He asks that these papers be not prosecuted in order to
                            favor return to normal conditions; I replied that the matter was not in
                            my hands but awaited the decision of my Government. Press attacks have
                            practically ceased and the better class of papers are becoming
                            distinctly friendly. The Cuban Government denies to the press that any
                            message has been received from the President.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
